06026nam a22008415i 9780812296686DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122966867 a10.9783/97808122966862doi  a(DE-B1597)531794  a(OCoLC)1134853716  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aK3258b.B54 2020 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a323.44/22231 aBielefeldt, Heiner, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Freedom Under Scrutiny /cHeiner Bielefeldt, Michael Wiener. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 illus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Universalism Tainted with Particularisms -- tChapter 2. Ambiguities of Freedom -- tChapter 3. Equality in Diversity -- tChapter 4. Awkward Bedfellows? Religious Freedom and Other Human Rights -- tChapter 5. Shades and Modes of Secularisms -- tChapter 6. Violations of Freedom of Religion or Belief -- tChapter 7. Comparing International and Regional Case Law -- tChapter 8. Preventing Violence Committed in the Name of Religion -- tChapter 9. Custodian Against the Sacralization of Human Rights -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFreedom of religion or belief is deeply entrenched in international human rights conventions and constitutional traditions around the world. Article 18 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights enshrines the right to freedom of thought, conscience, and religion as does the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which the United Nations General Assembly adopted in 1966. A rich jurisprudence on freedom of religion or belief is based on the European Convention on Human Rights, drafted in 1950 by the Council of Europe. Similar regional guarantees exist in the framework of the Organization of American States as well as within the African Union. Freedom of religion or belief has found recognition in numerous national constitutions, and some governments have shown a particularly strong commitment to the international promotion of this right.As Heiner Bielefeldt and Michael Wiener observe, however, freedom of religion or belief remains a source of political conflict, legal controversy, and intellectual debate. In Religious Freedom Under Scrutiny, Bielefeldt and Wiener explore various critiques leveled at this right. For example, does freedom of religion contribute to the spread of Western neoliberal values to the detriment of religious and cultural diversity? Can religious freedom serve as the entry point for antifeminist agendas within the human rights framework? Drawing on their considerable experience in the field, Bielefeldt and Wiener provide a typological overview and analysis of violations around the world that illustrate the underlying principles as well as the relationship between freedom of religion or belief and other human rights.Religious Freedom Under Scrutiny argues that without freedom of religion or belief, human rights cannot fully address our complex needs, yearnings, and vulnerabilities as human beings. Furthermore, ignoring or marginalizing freedom of religion or belief would weaken the plausibility, attractiveness, and legitimacy of the entire system of human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aFreedom of religion (International law). 0aFreedom of religion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.1 aWiener, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle